WEBVTT

00:16.900 --> 00:17.420
The

00:18.080 --> 00:23.580
next morning we fell early to work for the transportation of this great mass of gold

00:23.580 --> 00:29.640
near a mile by land to the beach, and thence three miles by boat to the Hispaniola, was

00:29.640 --> 00:35.080
a considerable task for so small a number of workmen. The three fellows still abroad

00:35.080 --> 00:40.120
upon the island did not greatly trouble us. A single sentry on the shoulder of the hill

00:40.120 --> 00:45.960
was sufficient to insure us against any sudden onslaught, and we thought, besides, they had

00:45.960 --> 00:52.720
had more than enough of fighting. Therefore the work was pushed on briskly. Gray and Ben

00:52.720 --> 00:58.040
Gunn came and went with the boat, while the rest, during their absences, piled treasures

00:58.040 --> 01:03.980
on the beach. Two of the bars, slung in a rope-sand, made a good load for a grown man,

01:04.180 --> 01:10.080
one that he was glad to walk slowly with. For my part, as I was not much use at carrying,

01:10.240 --> 01:16.700
I was kept busy all day in the cave, packing the minted money into bread-bags. It was a

01:16.700 --> 01:22.540
strange collection, like Billy Bone's hoard for the diversity of the coinage, but so much

01:22.540 --> 01:26.900
larger and so much more varied that I think I never had more pleasure than in sorting

01:26.900 --> 01:34.640
them. English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, Georges and Luises, doubloons and double guineas,

01:35.040 --> 01:39.860
and Morderes and sequins, the pictures of all the kings of Europe for the last hundred

01:39.860 --> 01:46.380
years, strange oriental pieces stamped with what looked like wisps of string or bits of

01:46.380 --> 01:52.380
spider's web, round pieces, square pieces, and pieces bored through the middle, as if

01:52.380 --> 01:58.680
neck. Nearly every variety of money in the world must, I think, have found a place in

01:58.680 --> 02:04.220
that collection, and for number I am sure they were like autumn leaves, so that my back

02:04.220 --> 02:11.060
ached with stooping and my fingers with sorting them out. Day after day this work went on.

02:11.320 --> 02:15.660
By every evening a fortune had been stowed aboard, but there was another fortune waiting

02:15.660 --> 02:20.660
for the morrow, and all this time we heard nothing of the three surviving mutineers.

02:21.680 --> 02:26.720
At last, I think it was on the third night, the doctor and I were strolling on the shoulder

02:26.720 --> 02:32.060
of the hill where it overlooks the lowlands of the isle, when from out of the thick darkness

02:32.060 --> 02:39.320
below, the wind brought us a noise between shrieking and singing. It was only a snatch

02:39.320 --> 02:42.440
that reached our ears, followed by the former silence.

02:43.600 --> 02:47.500
Heaven forgive them, said the doctor, tis the mutineers.

02:49.240 --> 02:53.520
All drunk, sir, struck in the voice of silver from behind us.

02:54.340 --> 02:59.980
Silver, I should say, was allowed his entire liberty, and in spite of daily rebuffs, seemed

02:59.980 --> 03:06.340
to regard himself once more as quite a privileged and friendly dependent. Indeed it was remarkable

03:06.340 --> 03:12.020
how well he bore these slights, and with what unwearying politeness he kept on trying to

03:12.020 --> 03:18.080
ingratiate himself with all. Yet I think none treated him better than a dog unless

03:18.080 --> 03:24.500
it was Ben Gunn, who was still terribly afraid of his old quartermaster, or myself, who had

03:24.500 --> 03:29.380
really something to thank him for. Although for that matter, I suppose, I had reason to

03:29.380 --> 03:34.920
think even worse of him than anyone else, for I had seen him meditating a fresh treachery

03:34.920 --> 03:40.080
upon the plateau. Accordingly, it was pretty gruffly that the doctor answered him.

03:40.080 --> 03:43.000
Drunk or raving, said he.

03:43.580 --> 03:49.100
Right you were, sir, replied Silver, and precious little odds which to you and me.

03:50.380 --> 03:56.080
I suppose you would hardly ask me to call you a humane man, returned the doctor with

03:56.080 --> 04:02.800
a sneer, and so my feelings may surprise you, Master Silver. But if I were sure they were

04:02.800 --> 04:08.620
raving, as I am mortally certain one at least of them is down with fever, I should leave

04:08.620 --> 04:14.420
this camp, and at whatever risk to my own carcass take them the assistance of my skill.

04:15.700 --> 04:22.000
Ask your pardon, sir, you would be very wrong, quote Silver. You would lose your precious

04:22.000 --> 04:27.960
life and you may lay to that. I am on your side now, hand in glove, and I shouldn't wish

04:27.960 --> 04:34.480
for to see the party weakened, let alone yourself, seeing as I know what I owes you. But these

04:34.480 --> 04:40.000
men down there, they couldn't keep their word, no, not supposing they wished to, and what's

04:40.000 --> 04:42.200
more, they couldn't believe as you could.

04:43.260 --> 04:47.780
No, said the doctor, you're the man to keep their word, we know that.

04:49.120 --> 04:54.580
Well, that was about the last news we had of the three pirates. Only once we heard a

04:54.580 --> 05:00.600
gunshot a great way off, and supposed them to be hunting. A council was held and it was

05:00.600 --> 05:06.340
decided that we must desert them on the island, to the huge glee, I must say, of Ben Gunn

05:06.340 --> 05:12.540
and with the strong approval of Gray. We left a good stock of powder and shot, the bulk

05:12.540 --> 05:18.320
of the salt-coat, a few medicines and some other necessaries, tools, clothing, a spare

05:18.320 --> 05:24.380
sail, a fathom or two of rope, and by the particular desire of the doctor, a handsome

05:24.380 --> 05:31.300
president of tobacco. That was about our last doing on the island. Before that, we

05:31.300 --> 05:35.240
had got the treasure stowed and had shipped enough water and the remainder of the goat

05:35.240 --> 05:41.100
meat in case of any distress. And at last, one fine morning, we weighed anchor, which

05:41.100 --> 05:46.280
was about all that we could manage, and stood out of North Inlet, the same colors flying

05:46.280 --> 05:52.240
that the captain had flown and fought under at the palisade. The three fellows must have

05:52.240 --> 05:56.840
been watching us closer than we thought for, as we soon had proved, for coming through

05:56.840 --> 06:02.580
the narrows, we had to lie very near the southern point, and there we saw all three of them,

06:02.940 --> 06:09.340
kneeling together on a spit of sand with their arms raised in supplication. It went to all

06:09.340 --> 06:14.300
our hearts, I think, to leave them in that wretched state, but we could not risk another

06:14.300 --> 06:19.640
mutiny, and to take them home for the gibbet would have been a cruel sort of kindness.

06:20.520 --> 06:25.480
The doctor hailed them and told them of the stores we had left, and where they were to

06:25.480 --> 06:31.180
find them, but they continued to call us by name and appeal to us, for God's sake, to

06:31.180 --> 06:38.320
be merciful and not leave them to die in such a place. At last, seeing the ship still bore

06:38.320 --> 06:43.700
on her course, and was now swiftly drawing out of earshot, one of them, I know not which

06:43.700 --> 06:49.660
it was, leaped to his feet with a hoarse cry, whipped his musket to his shoulder, and sent

06:49.660 --> 06:56.420
a shot whistling over Silver's head and through the mainsail. After that we kept under cover

06:56.420 --> 07:01.220
of the bulwarks, and when next I looked out they had disappeared from the spit, and the

07:01.220 --> 07:06.780
spit itself had almost melted out of sight in the growing distance. That was at least

07:06.780 --> 07:13.680
the end of that. And before noon, to my inexpressible joy, the highest rock of Treasure Island had

07:13.680 --> 07:20.180
sunk into the blue round of sea. We were so short of men that everyone on board had

07:20.180 --> 07:25.320
to bear a hand, only the captain lying on a mattress in the stern and giving his orders,

07:25.800 --> 07:30.960
for though greatly recovered he was still in want of quiet. We laid her head for the

07:30.960 --> 07:36.240
nearest port in Spanish America, for we could not risk the voyage home without fresh hands,

07:36.600 --> 07:42.180
and as it was, what with the baffling winds and a couple of fresh gales, we were all worn

07:42.180 --> 07:49.200
out before we reached it. It was just at sundown when we cast anchor in a most beautiful landlocked

07:49.200 --> 07:54.620
gulf, and were immediately surrounded by shore boats full of Negroes and Mexican Indians

07:54.620 --> 08:01.080
and half-bloods selling fruits and vegetables and offering to dive for bits of money. The

08:01.080 --> 08:06.540
sight of so many good-humored faces, especially the blacks, the taste of the tropical fruits,

08:06.540 --> 08:12.220
and above all the lights that began to shine in the town made a most charming contrast

08:12.220 --> 08:17.940
to our dark and bloody sojourn on the island, and the doctor and the squire, taking me along

08:17.940 --> 08:23.740
with him, went ashore to pass the early part of the night. Here they met the captain of

08:23.740 --> 08:29.240
an Englishman of war, fell in talk with him, went on board his ship, and in short had so

08:29.240 --> 08:33.940
agreeable a time that day was breaking when we came alongside the Hispaniola.

08:35.160 --> 08:40.260
Ben Gunn was on the deck alone, and as soon as we came on board he began, with wonderful

08:40.260 --> 08:48.540
contortions, to make us a confession. Silver was gone. The maroon had connived at his escape

08:48.540 --> 08:54.400
in a shore boat some hours ago, and he now assured us that he had only done so to preserve

08:54.400 --> 08:59.440
their lives, which would certainly have been forfeit if that man with the one leg that

08:59.440 --> 09:06.980
stayed aboard. But this was not all. The sea cook had not gone empty-handed. He had cut

09:06.980 --> 09:12.400
through a bulkhead unobserved and had removed one of the sacks of coin, worth perhaps three

09:12.400 --> 09:18.880
or four hundred guineas, to help him on his further wanderings. I think we were all pleased

09:18.880 --> 09:20.640
to be so cheaply quit of him.

09:21.900 --> 09:26.840
Well, to make a long story short, we got a few hands on board, made a good cruise home,

09:26.840 --> 09:31.920
when the Hispaniola reached Bristol just as Mr. Blandly was beginning to think of fitting

09:31.920 --> 09:38.380
out her consort. Five men, only of those who had sailed, returned with her. Drink, and

09:38.380 --> 09:43.320
the devil has done for the rest, with a vengeance, although to be sure, we were not quite in

09:43.320 --> 09:49.680
so bad a case as that other ship they sang about. With one man of her crew alive, what

09:49.680 --> 09:56.260
put to sea with seventy-five. All of us had an ample share of the treasure and used it

09:56.260 --> 10:02.220
wisely or foolishly, according to our natures. Captain Smollett is now retired from the sea.

10:03.440 --> 10:09.080
Gray not only saved his money, but being suddenly smit with the desire to rise, also studied

10:09.080 --> 10:14.900
his profession, and he is now mate and part owner of a fine, full-rigged ship, married

10:14.900 --> 10:21.740
besides, and the father of a family. As for Ben Gunn, he got a thousand pounds, which

10:21.740 --> 10:27.700
he spent or lost in three weeks, or, to be more exact, in nineteen days, for he was back

10:27.700 --> 10:33.660
begging on the twentieth. Then he was given a lodge to keep, exactly as he had feared

10:33.660 --> 10:38.920
upon the island. But he still lives, a great favorite, though something of a butt, with

10:38.920 --> 10:45.560
the country boys, and a notable singer in church on Sundays and Saints' days. Of silver

10:45.560 --> 10:51.680
we have heard no more. That formidable seafaring man with one leg has at last gone clean out

10:51.680 --> 10:57.560
of my life, and I dare say he met his old Negress, and perhaps still lives in comfort

10:57.560 --> 11:03.620
with her and Captain Flint. It is to be hoped so, I suppose, for his chance of comfort in

11:03.620 --> 11:10.900
another world are very small. The bar silver and the arms still lie, for all that I know,

11:10.900 --> 11:16.960
where Flint buried them, and certainly they shall lie there for me. Oxen and wane ropes

11:16.960 --> 11:22.400
would not bring me back again to that accursed island, and the worst dreams that ever I have

11:22.400 --> 11:28.180
are when I hear the surf booming about its coasts, or start upright in bed with the sharp

11:28.180 --> 11:36.700
voice of Captain Flint still ringing in my ears, Pieces of Eight! Pieces of Eight!

11:38.620 --> 11:44.440
End of chapter thirty-four, and End of Treasure Island, by Robert Louis Stevenson.

